{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/medcattrainer-a-tool-for-inspecting-improving-and-customising-medcat-880a11297ebe", "time": 1683005335.17056, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/medcattrainer-a-tool-for-inspecting-improving-and-customising-medcat-880a11297ebe/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "MedCATTrainer: A Tool For Inspecting, Improving and Customising MedCAT | by Tom Searle | Towards Data Science", "h1": "MedCATTrainer: A Tool For Inspecting, Improving and Customising MedCAT", "description": "The Medical Concept Annotation Tool (MedCAT), is a (Named Entity Recognition + Linking) NER+L tool for identifying and linking clinical text concepts to existing biomedical ontologies such as UMLS or\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://github.com/CogStack/MedCAT", "anchor_text": "Medical Concept Annotation Tool (MedCAT)", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://www.nlm.nih.gov/research/umls/index.html", "anchor_text": "UMLS", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://digital.nhs.uk/services/terminology-and-classifications/snomed-ct", "anchor_text": "SNOMED-CT", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://github.com/CogStack/MedCATtrainer", "anchor_text": "open-source", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://github.com/CogStack/MedCATtrainer/blob/master/README.md#installation", "anchor_text": "3 commands", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://github.com/CogStack/MedCAT", "anchor_text": "MedCAT models", "paragraph_index": 4}, {"url": "https://github.com/CogStack/MedCATtrainer/blob/master/docs/example_data/psych.csv", "anchor_text": "dataset", "paragraph_index": 4}, {"url": "https://github.com/CogStack/MedCATtrainer/blob/master/README.md#doc-summary", "anchor_text": "document summary", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://github.com/CogStack/MedCATtrainer/blob/master/README.md#main-text", "anchor_text": "clinical text", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://github.com/CogStack/MedCATtrainer/blob/master/README.md#section-5---concept-summary", "anchor_text": "currently selected concept", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://github.com/CogStack/MedCATtrainer/blob/master/README.md#submit", "anchor_text": "submission", "paragraph_index": 8}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inter-rater_reliability", "anchor_text": "IIA", "paragraph_index": 10}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cohen%27s_kappa", "anchor_text": "Cohen\u2019s Kappa", "paragraph_index": 10}, {"url": "https://github.com/CogStack/MedCATtrainer/blob/master/README.md#clone-project", "anchor_text": "clone", "paragraph_index": 10}, {"url": "https://github.com/CogStack/MedCATtrainer/blob/master/README.md#create-project", "anchor_text": "permission", "paragraph_index": 10}, {"url": "https://github.com/CogStack/MedCATtrainer#download-annos", "anchor_text": "download", "paragraph_index": 10}, {"url": "https://github.com/CogStack/MedCATtrainer/blob/master/docs/Processing_Annotations.ipynb", "anchor_text": "report metric performance", "paragraph_index": 10}, {"url": "https://github.com/CogStack/MedCATtrainer/blob/master/README.md#meta-annotation-configuration", "anchor_text": "Administrators can configure annotation projects", "paragraph_index": 12}, {"url": "https://github.com/CogStack/MedCATtrainer/blob/master/README.md#download-annos", "anchor_text": "download", "paragraph_index": 13}, {"url": "https://github.com/CogStack/MedCAT/blob/master/medcat/meta_cat.py", "anchor_text": "MedCAT library", "paragraph_index": 13}, {"url": "https://github.com/CogStack/MedCATtrainer", "anchor_text": "GitHub", "paragraph_index": 14}, {"url": "https://github.com/CogStack/MedCATtrainer/blob/master/docs/API_Examples.ipynb", "anchor_text": "programmatic API access", "paragraph_index": 14}], "all_paragraphs": ["The Medical Concept Annotation Tool (MedCAT), is a (Named Entity Recognition + Linking) NER+L tool for identifying and linking clinical text concepts to existing biomedical ontologies such as UMLS or SNOMED-CT \u2014 often a first step in deriving insight from the masses of unstructured plain text available in clinical EHRs.", "This article will introduce MedCATTrainer an accompanying tool to MedCAT that can be used to:", "These 3 tasks are important in the application of MedCAT across clinical use cases.", "MedCATTrainer provides an annotation interface, ReST API, Middle tier and database. All components have been dockerized and are available open-source. To download, install and run in takes 3 commands.", "Running the application for the first time downloads MedCAT models, an example dataset and creates an example project permissioned for configured example user.", "The interface shows a document summary and its annotation status, the current clinical text under review and the currently selected concept details sourced from MedCAT.", "An easy to use, simple, but feature-rich web interface allows annotators to:", "An optional setting within the project configuration allows for entirely new concepts to be added by human annotators. New concepts can be further grouped by semantic types akin to UMLS and SNOMED-CT Root terms. This feature is especially relevant for areas such as mental health that are often underserved by standardised terminologies such as UMLS and SNOMED-CT.", "MedCATTrainer can be used to actively train the configured MedCAT model. After every submission of a document each of the correct, incorrect and newly added entities are used to further train the configured MedCAT model. As human annotators process more documents the \u2018assisted\u2019 annotation experience makes the annotation less arduous.", "The chart below shows a recent project to annotate symptoms, findings, and medication concepts in real clinical text, as the human annotators proceed they encounter fewer new SNOMED-CT entities that are added manually. The varying peaks indicate the variability of real clinical data. The convergence of the MedCAT model demonstrates the value of investing in human annotation and can be considered a form of model \u2018fine-tuning\u2019.", "Once \u2018fine-tuned\u2019 to a dataset or clinical note type, rigorous evaluation of the MedCAT model performance can be performed, by dual annotators without active learning to compute standard metrics such as IIA and Cohen\u2019s Kappa. MedCATTrainer supports this use case by allowing administrators to easily clone projects and permission annotators individually, then download and report metric performance.", "Using clinical text in a downstream research question often entails more than simply identifying the correct text span and linking with the correct terminology concept (UMLS /SNOMED-CT). It also often involves further annotation of a disease or symptom ensuring they are patient related, or is a current instance and is not simply a clinician mentioning the concept hypothetically. However, often research questions will have varying interpretations of, for example, temporality \u2014 \u2018current\u2019 and \u2018historical\u2019 may not provide the appropriate level of granularity for all research questions.", "MedCATTrainer supports the configuration of project or use-case specific collection of these, so-called, meta-annotations. Administrators can configure annotation projects with specific meta-annotations to be re-used between projects or in isolation. Each configured annotation and associated values appear in the interface.", "Once complete, administrators can download the annotations and train individual meta-annotation models using the MedCAT library.", "This short introduction has motivated the use of MedCATTrainer alongside the MedCAT tool. A full set of documentation is available directly on the GitHub, alongside full details for programmatic API access, detailed configuration of all of the above features and project design patterns for common use cases for organising, structuring and analysing EHRs.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Clinical NLP PhD - interes